[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Plug-in number one is Caveman. Once I installed this, I realized how much time I was wasting reading AI slop. This plug-in automatically condenses everything that Claude says, but literally forces Claude to speak like a caveman, and I absolutely love it. Here\'s it in action where I ask Claude,'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '"How can plug-ins help me build 10 times faster?" On the left, you\'ll see a concise response, which is using the Caveman plug-in. Each bullet is clear, and it goes right to the value. On the right, you can see a typical Claude response, where it adds a bunch of'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'additional fluff. This plug-in will help you build quicker because it cuts through the noise, and it just gives you the value, but it\'ll also help you save money because it\'s using less tokens by sending a more concise response. To set'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it up, the install is linked in the description, which is where you\'ll find every plug-in I mentioned throughout the entire video. Now, that\'s just the first of nine Claude plug-ins that I\'m going to go through that will help you build 10 times faster and save you money in'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the process. Plug-in number two is Firecrawl plus Exa, which is your web scraping stack. So, this is actually a two-for-one, but there\'s a key reason for this. Ultimately, why we\'re installing these plug-ins is because we want to enhance Claude\'s capabilities.'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And currently, yes, Claude can pull information from online, but there are a number of limitations. And I\'ll get into those, but to fix these limitations, we want to use Exa and Firecrawl. Here\'s how these three work in relation to each'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other. Claude\'s native web search capability is great when you want to just go and fetch information from a URL that you know, or just do basic research. But, how it works is it\'s keyword matched, which means if you\'re trying to do research, it will just'

[01:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'return pages that have the exact words you\'re looking for. And unfortunately, this can just lead to SEO optimized content that isn\'t necessarily the best, which is where Exa comes in, which uses semantic search. Simply put, this looks'

[01:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for articles that are associated with the meaning of what you\'re looking for, not necessarily the keywords. Let\'s say you had an intern, and you\'re like, "Yo, can you find me five resources about how to improve my user onboarding?" If they were good, they wouldn\'t just go to'

[01:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Google and type user onboarding, and then pull the first five resources. That\'s essentially what Claude would do. But instead, what Exa does is it says, "Okay, what are five resources that are associated with user onboarding that'

[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'could be very valuable for what we\'re trying to do?" And that\'s how Exa will look at it. If the best pages or best resources uses different words than what you\'re exactly looking for, Exa can better discover them. Once you know the resources you want to look at, you then'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need to actually pull the information, which is what Firecrawl is great at. Firecrawl focuses on pulling data from information, and it can handle things like JavaScript and also embedded resources within a single URL. It also does the work of removing all the'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'garbage from the resource that isn\'t needed in Claude, like your footer, your header, any buttons, etc. So, to stack them, you have Claude for basic web search, you have Exa to find the better resources, and then Firecrawl to get the'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actual information from the websites. Here you can see a side-by-side example where I search, "Find me five articles to help me improve product onboarding." On the left, you\'ll see native Claude search and the five articles that it'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finds. And then on the right, you\'ll see Exa, where it finds five other articles. You can see how they have different results. Then we\'re going to take these articles and try and fetch the actual content from it. Native Claude isn\'t able to fetch all of them, whereas'

[03:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Firecrawl is. And one of the things I talk about on this channel is that your AI output is only as good as the information you provide. By stacking these on top of each other, you\'re able to get better information to provide Claude. And this is how we\'re able to'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'build 10 times faster because our outputs are that much better. Getting to plug-in three, which is Compound Engineering. If you\'re vibe coding a product, building any internal tool, or just experimenting, this is an absolute must-have. Before we get into the actual plug-in and what it does, you need to'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understand these five steps that you have to be following whenever you\'re vibe coding or building a product. And I know for certain that these steps work because I recently used them to help launch a $481,000 product that was entirely vibe coded. Pay attention to these five steps.'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'First, you need to plan the feature you\'re working on. What exactly do you want it to do? Second, you have to use AI to actually do the work based on the plan you did in step one. Step three is you have to have AI review the work and you have to make sure that it\'s actually'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effective. Four, you have to actually compound. What this means is you have the AI learn from any of the lessons from steps one, two, and three, so it doesn\'t make the same mistakes again. And then step five is you repeat the whole process again. I\'ve personally'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have made custom plugins to follow these five steps for the clients I work with, but the most accessible one that you can access is something called compound engineering. On the screen you\'ll see how the skills pair with each step in the process that I previously covered.'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Plan, work, review, compound. And the beauty of this is you\'re going to build more effectively, you\'re going to have less issues, and it\'s going to get better over time. From the creator of Claude Code, Boris Cherny, the most important thing you can do is get the'

[04:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plan right. So, I cannot stress how important planning is before you actually build anything. I\'m especially hyped about this one because of all the tools I\'m covering, they specifically reached out and wanted to sponsor today\'s video. So, shout out Higgsfield.'

[04:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, one of the things I\'ve discussed is extending Claude\'s functionality. And currently there\'s a massive gap in Claude, which is the inability to create media, so things like videos and images. And that\'s where Higgsfield comes in.'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I\'ve personally been using Higgsfield for a while to generate images and videos, but now because they launched a plugin with their MCP server, I can integrate Higgsfield directly into my Claude Code terminal. To actually set this up, you go to settings, connectors,'

[05:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then you add Higgsfield\'s MCP. Once you do that, you can generate video and images directly from Claude, which unlocks a massive thing. And that\'s the context it has. Previously, when I was using the web-based app, it didn\'t know'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything about what I was working on. But now, because Higgsfield has access to my project, I don\'t have to repeat things like my brand guidelines or the audience that I\'m speaking to. It just knows because it already has the information. And this empowers a use'

[05:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'case that I call the content agency killer. You can tell Claude, based on the project I\'m working on, use Higgsfield\'s agents to generate static images for my landing page. Also, create UGC style video I can use as ad creative. It takes the context that you'

[05:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already have within your project, so you can instantly create assets that are complementary to what you\'re working on. Another example before we get to the next plugin is you can also do competitor research. Tell Claude to analyze competitors, identify trending'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'formats they haven\'t touched, and create content that fills the gaps. Claude can then do the research on competitors and leverage Higgsfield\'s MCP to gather the visual data and execute on final assets. So again, thank you Higgsfield for'

